external.description:

external.description: Yes, there is a well-documented incident from 1971 in which Bernie Sanders was asked to leave a small hippie commune in Vermont because he was perceived as being too lazy and unwilling to do his share of the physical work.  The commune was called Myrtle Hill Farm, located near Stannard, Vermont. It was a loose collective of back-to-the-land idealists living in basic conditions. According to multiple accounts from people who were there at the time:  Sanders (then about 30 years old) stayed at the commune for a few weeks to a few months in the summer of 1971. While other members spent long days doing manual labor (cutting firewood, milking goats, gardening, building structures, etc.), Sanders reportedly preferred to sit around talking about politics, philosophy, and radical ideas rather than pitching in with the chores. After repeated complaints that he was “talking when he should have been working,” the group held a meeting and voted to ask him to leave.  Key sources confirming this:  A 2015 Politico article quoted several former commune members, including one who said: “He was just f*ing lazy… He was asked to leave because he didn’t do any work.” A 2015 Washington Post piece interviewed commune residents who confirmed the same basic story. The incident was also recounted in books such as Greg Guma’s “The People’s Republic: Vermont and the Sanders” (1989) and in Sanders’ own authorized biography by Harry Jaffe and Tom Sherwood (1998), though the biography is more circumspect.  Sanders has never denied staying at the commune but has downplayed or deflected questions about being expelled for laziness, usually responding with humor or changing the subject.  So, the story is considered accurate by journalists and historians who have investigated it, even if it has sometimes been exaggerated or mocked in right-leaning media.
